<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-328-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 328 928.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  June 1989 v6 n6 pS41(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The language of choice; why non-English software is crucial toUNIX's success.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kasbarian, Raymond.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The growing demand for computer operating systems, applicationsand programming tools in the local language of foreign countriesis requiring software vendors, corporate users, and governments todevelop such products and necessary standard formats.andP;  Thisrequires addressing appropriate character sets, keyboards tailoredto the language, appropriate context use of characters, and systemmessages in the local language.andP;  Approaches and standards fornon-English and multilingual programming systems have been or arebeing developed by a variety of domestic, foreign andinternational organizations.andP;  Foreign-language UNIXimplementations, for example, are being perused by such groups asusr-group's Internationalization Committee, IEEE's POSIXcommittee, and X-Open's Common Applications Environment group.andO;Software publisher and government foreign-language UNIX activitiesare also described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     UNIXForeign LanguagesMultilingual CapabilitySystem DevelopmentRequirements AnalysisGoals and ObjectivesTrendsCode Conversion.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>